We motivate our method by first considering the directional gradient by the two-point estimation in Section 3.2. With decoupled \( f(\cdot; \theta) \) and \( L(\cdot) \) as in the pseudo-zeroth-order formulation and Taylor expansion of \( L(\cdot) \), Eq. 3 turns into: 
\begin{equation} \nabla^{\text{ZO}}_\theta L(L'(\nabla_oL(o, y_x), \tilde{o} - o) \approx \frac{\Delta o}{\alpha}^{\text{T}}z-\nabla_oL(o, y_x),\tag{5} \end{equation}
where \( o = f(x; \theta) \), \( \tilde{o} = f(x; \theta + \alpha z) \), and \( \Delta o = \tilde{o} - o \). This can be viewed as propagating the error signal with a connection weight \( \frac{z}{\alpha} \Delta o \). To reduce the variance introduced by the random direction z, we introduce momentum feedback connections across different iterations and propagate errors as: 
\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} M := \lambda M + (1 - \lambda)\frac{z}{\alpha} \Delta o,\\ \nabla^{\text{PZO}}_\theta L := M\nabla_oL(o, y_x). \end{aligned}\tag{6} \end{equation}
The momentum feedback connections can take advantage of different sampled directions z, largely alleviating the variance caused by random directions. The above formulation only considers the directional gradient with two-point estimation, while we are more interested in methods with a single forward pass. Actually, \( \frac{z}{\alpha} \Delta o \) can be viewed as an unbiased estimator of \( E_x [J^\text{F}(x)] \), where \( J^\text{F}(x) \) is the Jacobian of f evaluated at x, and M can be viewed as approximating it with moving average. Therefore, we can similarly use a one-point method and M has similar effects: 
\begin{equation} M := \lambda M + (1 - \lambda)\frac{z}{\alpha}, \tag{7} \end{equation}
where \( \frac{z}{\alpha} \) is also an unbiased estimator of \( E_x [J^\text{F}(x)] \).
Lemma 4.1. When z has i.i.d. components with zero mean and unit variance independent of inputs, in the limit \( \alpha \rightarrow 0 \), \( \frac{z}{\alpha} \Delta o \) and \( \frac{z}{\alpha} \) are unbiased estimators of \( J^\text{F} (x) \) given x, and further, are unbiased estimators of \( E_x [J^\text{F}(x)] \). This leads to our method as shown in Fig. 1(e). During forward propagation, a random noise \( \alpha z \) is injected for each

We build the above pseudo-zeroth-order approach on online training methods to deal with spatial and temporal credit assignments. As introduced in Section 3.1, we consider OTTT (Xiao et al., 2022) and replace its backpropagated instantaneous gradient with our estimated gradient based on direct top-down feedback. Then the update for synaptic weights has a similar form as the three-factor Hebbian learning (Frémaux & Gerstner, 2016) based on a direct top-down global modulator: 
\begin{equation} \Delta W_{i,j} \propto \hat{a}_i[t]\psi(u_j[t])g_j.\tag{8} \end{equation}
where \( W_{i,j} \) is the weight from neuron i to j, \( \hat{a}_i[t] \) is the presynaptic activity trace, \( \psi(u_j[t]) \) is a local surrogate derivative for the change rate of the postsynaptic activity (Xiao et al., 2022), and \( g_j \) is the global top-down error (gradient) modulator. Here we leverage the local surrogate derivative because it can be well-defined under the stochastic setting (see Appendix B for details) and better fits the biological three-factor Hebbian rule. For potentially asynchronous neuromorphic computing, there may be a delay in the propagation of error signals.
